HitCounter Sliding Window Diagram
Time axis (seconds) → [t-299] ... [t-3] [t-2] [t-1] [t]

Buckets (size = 300):
+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+ ... +-----+
|  0  |  1  |  2  |  3  |  4  | ... | 299 |
+-----+-----+-----+-----+-----+ ... +-----+
timestamps[idx] -> actual last timestamp stored in that bucket
counts[idx]     -> number of hits at that timestamp

Example scenario:
t = 302s
bucket index = t % SIZE = 302 % 300 = 2

Hit arrives at t=302:
1. Check bucket 2:
   - If timestamps[2] != 302 → reset counts[2] = 0
   - Set timestamps[2] = 302
   - counts[2]++
   
Current sliding window: [t-299, t] = [3, 302]
- Only sum counts from buckets where timestamps[idx] > t - SIZE
- Ignore old buckets (timestamps[idx] <= 2)

Step-by-Step Explanation with Example

| Timestamp    | Bucket Index (mod 300) | Action                         | Counts Array Snapshot (simplified)                  |
| ------------ | ---------------------- | ------------------------------ | --------------------------------------------------- |
| 300          | 0                      | hit                            | counts[0] = 1                                       |
| 301          | 1                      | hit                            | counts[1] = 1                                       |
| 302          | 2                      | hit                            | counts[2] = 1                                       |
| 303          | 3                      | hit                            | counts[3] = 1                                       |
| getHits(303) | -                      | sum counts where timestamp > 3 | total = counts[0]+counts[1]+counts[2]+counts[3] = 4 |


Visual Concept
Sliding Window (last 5 minutes = 300s)
[t-299]-------------------[t-2][t-1][t]
| old buckets (ignored) | active buckets (sum counts) |

HitCounter array → cyclic buffer
[0][1][2][3]...[299]
 ^  ^  ^
 |  |  |
 old new current


Each bucket corresponds to 1 second of the window.

The modulo ensures rolling over once timestamp exceeds 300.

Only active buckets contribute to getHits().

✅ Key Takeaways

Fixed memory: Only 300 buckets.

O(1) hit(): constant time, no iteration needed.

Sliding window: accurate hit count for last 5 min.

Highly interview-friendly: can extend to per-user counters, distributed systems, or longer windows.